question: Does the HSPB1 gene have pathogenic variants documented in ClinVar for Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease?
ideal_answer: Yes, HSPB1 (heat shock protein family B (small) member 1, Gene ID 3315) has multiple pathogenic and likely pathogenic variants documented in ClinVar that are specifically linked to Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2F (CMT2F; MedGen C1847823), the HSPB1-associated axonal subtype of CMT. The exact count depends on the database snapshot; the RDF portal query returned 20 current records at time of query, while the live NCBI ClinVar release contains ≥66 such variants. Variants include missense substitutions affecting functionally critical residues in the alpha-crystallin domain (e.g., c.379C>T p.Arg127Trp, c.404C>T p.Ser135Phe, c.406C>T p.Arg136Trp, c.418C>G p.Arg140Gly, c.545C>T p.Pro182Leu), as well as frameshift and nonsense variants (e.g., c.109dup p.Arg37fs (Likely pathogenic), c.532G>T p.Glu178Ter (Likely pathogenic)). Several large deletions at the HSPB1 locus on chromosome 7q11.23 also appear in the dataset. CMT2F is an autosomal dominant axonal peripheral sensorimotor neuropathy characterised by distal muscle weakness, sensory loss, and reduced tendon reflexes with onset ranging from the first to sixth decade.
baseline_answer: Yes, the HSPB1 gene (Heat Shock Protein Family B Member 1) has pathogenic variants documented in ClinVar associated with Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, specifically type 2F (CMT2F) and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 2B (dHMN2B). HSPB1 encodes a small heat shock protein also known as HSP27, which functions as a molecular chaperone involved in protein folding, cytoskeletal stabilization, and cellular stress response. Mutations in HSPB1 typically follow an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern and cause axonal forms of peripheral neuropathy. The pathogenic variants documented in ClinVar include various missense mutations that cluster in functionally important domains of the protein, particularly affecting the alpha-crystallin domain that is critical for the protein's chaperone activity and oligomerization. These mutations lead to motor and sensory neuropathy characterized by progressive distal muscle weakness and atrophy, sensory loss, and reduced nerve conduction velocities, with disease onset typically occurring in adolescence or early adulthood.
togomcp_answer: Yes, the HSPB1 gene has pathogenic variants documented in ClinVar for Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, with 68 variants identified that are classified as pathogenic or likely pathogenic. The HSPB1 gene is associated with Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 2F (CMT2F) and distal hereditary motor neuropathy type 2B (dHMN2B), both of which are neuromuscular disorders. These pathogenic variants represent missense mutations and other alterations in the heat shock protein beta-1 (HSPB1) that cause peripheral neuropathy through disruption of the protein's chaperone function, leading to motor and sensory nerve degeneration characteristic of Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease.

The annotations encompass proteins involved in immune cell recruitment, neural development, and microbial motility. Major functional categories include chemokine receptors, integrins, and signaling molecules that regulate directed cell migration in response to chemical gradients.

question: Summarize the distribution of melatonin biosynthesis enzymes across species and characterize their molecular functions and the chemical intermediates involved.
ideal_answer: Melatonin biosynthesis enzymes are distributed across 16 species spanning three kingdoms (Animalia, Plantae, and Fungi), with 33 reviewed proteins in total. Mammals account for 14 proteins across 9 taxa, including two human paralogs (AANAT and ASMT), with coverage extending to mouse, rat, cattle, sheep, macaque, hamster, chimpanzee, and Mus musculus molossinus. Plants contribute 14 proteins from 4 taxa: Arabidopsis thaliana (4 proteins), Oryza sativa subsp. japonica (7 proteins, the most of any single organism), Oryza sativa subsp. indica (1 protein), and Zea mays (2 proteins). Additional representatives include two bird proteins in Gallus gallus, two insect proteins in Drosophila melanogaster, and one fungal protein in Saccharomyces cerevisiae. The pathway proceeds through two enzymatic steps acting on distinct chemical intermediates: first, aralkylamine N-acetyltransferase (AANAT, GO:0004059, a subclass of N-acetyltransferase activity) converts serotonin (CHEBI:28790, C10H12N2O) to N-acetylserotonin (CHEBI:17697, C12H14N2O2); then acetylserotonin O-methyltransferase (ASMT, GO:0017096, a subclass of S-adenosylmethionine-dependent methyltransferase activity) converts N-acetylserotonin to melatonin (CHEBI:16796, C13H16N2O2). Exactly 17 proteins are annotated with AANAT activity and 16 with ASMT activity, with no overlap. This enzymatic conservation across evolutionarily distant taxa — from yeast to plants to mammals — indicates an ancient origin of the two-step melatonin biosynthesis mechanism, with the pathway starting from tryptophan (CHEBI:27897, C11H12N2O2) via serotonin as the upstream precursor.
baseline_answer: Melatonin biosynthesis enzymes exhibit broad phylogenetic distribution across bacteria, plants, fungi, and animals, though the enzymatic pathways and gene families differ significantly among taxa. The canonical vertebrate pathway begins with tryptophan, which is converted to 5-hydroxytryptophan by tryptophan hydroxylase, then to serotonin by aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase. Serotonin serves as the key intermediate for melatonin synthesis through two sequential enzymatic steps: arylalkylamine N-acetyltransferase (AANAT) converts serotonin to N-acetylserotonin, and hydroxyindole-O-methyltransferase (HIOMT, also called ASMT) methylates N-acetylserotonin to produce melatonin. AANAT functions as the rate-limiting enzyme in vertebrates, catalyzing acetyl-CoA-dependent acetylation with high substrate specificity for serotonin. HIOMT utilizes S-adenosylmethionine as the methyl donor to transfer a methyl group to the 5-hydroxyl position of N-acetylserotonin. In plants, melatonin synthesis follows a similar chemical pathway but employs distinct enzyme families, including tryptophan decarboxylase, tryptamine 5-hydroxylase, serotonin N-acetyltransferase, and N-acetylserotonin O-methyltransferase, with some species utilizing alternative routes that produce N-acetylserotonin from 5-methoxytryptamine. Invertebrates display variable expression patterns, with AANAT homologs identified in arthropods but often showing different regulatory mechanisms and tissue distributions compared to vertebrates. The methyltransferase step shows particular diversity, with different organisms utilizing non-homologous enzymes that convergently evolved similar catalytic functions, reflecting independent evolutionary origins of melatonin biosynthesis capacity across domains of life.
togomcp_answer: Melatonin biosynthesis enzymes are distributed across diverse species including mammals, birds, amphibians, insects, plants, and bacteria, with the core pathway involving four key enzymatic steps that convert L-tryptophan to melatonin (N-acetyl-5-methoxytryptamine). The pathway begins with tryptophan 5-hydroxylase (EC 1.14.16.4), which catalyzes the rate-limiting hydroxylation of L-tryptophan to 5-hydroxy-L-tryptophan using tetrahydrobiopterin and molecular oxygen as cofactors. Aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (EC 4.1.1.28) then removes the carboxyl group from 5-hydroxy-L-tryptophan to produce serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine), the central neurotransmitter intermediate. Aralkylamine N-acetyltransferase (AANAT, EC 2.3.1.87), also known as serotonin N-acetyltransferase, acetylates serotonin using acetyl-CoA as the acetyl donor to form N-acetylserotonin, representing the penultimate and regulatory step that controls circadian rhythms in melatonin production. Finally, acetylserotonin O-methyltransferase (ASMT, EC 2.1.1.4), also called hydroxyindole O-methyltransferase, catalyzes the terminal methylation of N-acetylserotonin using S-adenosyl-L-methionine as the methyl donor to produce melatonin. These enzymes show broad taxonomic distribution, with reviewed UniProt entries documenting tryptophan 5-hydroxylase in 11 species, aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase in 15 species, serotonin N-acetyltransferase in 14 species, and acetylserotonin O-methyltransferase in 9 species, spanning vertebrates (humans, mice, rats, cattle, chickens, macaques), invertebrates (Drosophila, Caenorhabditis elegans), and plants (Arabidopsis thaliana, rice). In mammals, AANAT is particularly abundant in the pineal gland where cAMP-dependent phosphorylation regulates its stability through interaction with 14-3-3 proteins, while ASMT is located in the pseudoautosomal region of the X and Y chromosomes in humans, and plants possess chloroplast-localized variants that participate in stress responses beyond classical circadian regulation.

question:
Among the following kinase groups — AGC, CAMK, CMGC, and TK — which has the greatest number of human protein targets with experimentally determined X-ray crystal structures deposited in the PDB?

Choose one of the following options:
  - AGC
  - CAMK
  - CMGC
  - TK
ideal_answer:
TK (tyrosine kinases) has the greatest number of human protein targets with
PDB X-ray crystal structures, with 2,280 structures across 80 ChEMBL-classified
human targets. CMGC ranks second (1,539 structures, 58 targets), followed by
CAMK (734 structures, 65 targets) and AGC (422 structures, 59 targets).

TK dominates structural coverage because tyrosine kinases are the primary targets
in cancer drug discovery. The EGFR family alone (EGFR, HER2, HER3, HER4) accounts
for hundreds of entries; BCR-ABL1 (P00519) has over 200 structures due to
imatinib-resistance studies; VEGFR2/KDR (P35968), ALK (Q9UM73), c-MET (P08581),
RET (P07949), FGFR1-4, and the SRC family kinases each contribute dozens to
hundreds of structures. The pharmaceutical industry's intense focus on TK
inhibitors for oncology has driven an outsized crystallographic effort relative
to the number of targets.

CMGC ranks second because it includes intensively studied targets: CDK2 (P24941)
alone has over 400 PDB structures from fragment-based and structure-based drug
design campaigns; CDK4/6 (cyclin-dependent kinases), CDK8, CDK9, MAPK1/ERK2
(P28482), MAPK14/p38α (Q16539), GSK3B (P49841), and DYRK1A (Q13627) are all
major drug targets with large structural datasets.

CAMK ranks third despite having the most targets (65) among the four groups,
because many CAMK members (e.g., CaM kinases, DAPK, CHK1, CHK2) are less
pharmacologically tractable or have been structurally solved fewer times.

AGC ranks last (422 structures) despite its prominent members (AKT1/2/3, PKCα,
PKA, RSK1-4, S6K1) because several AGC kinases proved challenging for structural
biology due to flexibility or membrane association, and the group has fewer
members overall.

A note on cross-group overlap: 70 PDB structures (1.4%) contain proteins with
dual classification in ChEMBL (6 proteins annotated as both AGC and CAMK). These
structures are counted in both groups' totals. This overlap does not affect the
answer — TK leads CMGC by 741 structures, far exceeding the 70-structure overlap.
baseline_answer:
**TK**

The TK (Tyrosine Kinase) group has the greatest number of human protein targets with experimentally determined X-ray crystal structures deposited in the PDB among these four kinase groups. This predominance reflects the extensive structural biology efforts focused on tyrosine kinases, driven largely by their critical roles in cancer and other diseases, making them high-priority drug targets. The TK group includes receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) like EGFR, VEGFR, and insulin receptor, as well as non-receptor tyrosine kinases like Src, Abl, and JAK family members, many of which have been crystallized multiple times in different conformational states and with various inhibitors. The pharmaceutical industry's intense interest in developing tyrosine kinase inhibitors for cancer therapy has fueled structural studies of these proteins, resulting in hundreds of PDB entries for TK group members, significantly exceeding the structural coverage of AGC (containing PKA, PKC, AKT), CAMK (including CaMKII, CHK1), and CMGC (containing CDKs, MAPKs, GSK3, CLKs) kinase groups.

question: How many human metalloprotease drug targets with experimental 3D structures are documented in ChEMBL?
ideal_answer: There are 69 human metalloprotease drug targets with experimental 3D structures documented in ChEMBL. These were identified by integrating three databases: UniProt proteins annotated with metallopeptidase activity (GO:0008237 and all 12 descendant GO terms, confirmed via OLS4:getDescendants), ChEMBL, and PDB. From 185 human metalloproteases (reviewed SwissProt entries), 92 are registered as ChEMBL single-protein drug targets, and 91 have at least one experimental PDB structure cross-referenced in UniProt. The intersection — proteins that are both ChEMBL drug targets and structurally characterized — is 69, representing 75% structural coverage of the metalloprotease drug target space. This high coverage reflects the pharmaceutical importance of metalloproteases, particularly matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs), ADAMs, and aminopeptidases, which are extensively pursued for cancer, arthritis, and cardiovascular disease. The integration of ChEMBL bioactivity data with PDB structural data across the complete metalloprotease family reveals that the vast majority of drug-relevant metalloproteases have been structurally characterized, providing a foundation for structure-based drug design.
baseline_answer: I cannot provide a specific number for human metalloprotease drug targets with experimental 3D structures documented in ChEMBL, as this requires querying the ChEMBL database directly, which I do not have access to. ChEMBL is a manually curated database of bioactive molecules with drug-like properties, maintained by the European Bioinformatics Institute (EMBL-EBI), and it contains information about drug targets, including their 3D structures when available from sources like the Protein Data Bank (PDB). The exact count of human metalloproteases classified as drug targets with experimental structures would depend on ChEMBL's current curation standards, the specific criteria used to define "drug targets" (such as targets with active compounds meeting certain bioactivity thresholds), and the database version being queried. Human metalloproteases include numerous enzyme families such as matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs), a disintegrin and metalloproteinases (ADAMs), and zinc-dependent peptidases, many of which have been structurally characterized and are therapeutic targets for conditions including cancer, inflammation, and cardiovascular disease. To obtain the precise current number, one would need to perform a structured query of the ChEMBL database filtering for human proteins, metalloprotease classification, drug target status, and available experimental 3D structure data.

question: Does the SPG11 gene, a causative gene for hereditary spastic paraplegia type 11, satisfy all three of the following conditions: (1) a MANE Select transcript in Ensembl, (2) an experimentally-determined protein structure in PDB, and (3) a drug target entry in ChEMBL?
ideal_answer: Yes, the SPG11 gene (ENSG00000104133) associated with hereditary spastic paraplegia type 11 satisfies all three conditions. (1) MANE Select transcript: ENST00000261866 in Ensembl carries the MANE Select quality flag (ENSGLOSSARY_0000365), indicating it is the highest-quality representative isoform chosen through collaboration between NCBI and Ensembl. (2) PDB structures: the encoded protein Spatacsin (UniProt: Q96JI7, mnemonic SPTCS_HUMAN, Swiss-Prot reviewed) has three cryo-EM structures deposited: 8YAD (SPG11-SPG15 complex), 8YAB (AP5 complex bound to SPG11-SPG15), and 8YAH (full-length AP5 complex bound to SPG11-SPG15), all determined by electron microscopy single-particle reconstruction. (3) ChEMBL drug target: Spatacsin is registered as a SINGLE PROTEIN target in ChEMBL (CHEMBL6067204), linked to Q96JI7 via a TargetComponent/skos:exactMatch cross-reference, with at least one binding assay (CHEMBL5652514) on record.
baseline_answer: The SPG11 gene does not satisfy all three conditions simultaneously. SPG11, which encodes spatacsin and causes hereditary spastic paraplegia type 11 (SPG11) when mutated, has a MANE Select transcript designated in Ensembl (ENST00000262948.10, corresponding to RefSeq NM_025137.4). However, the gene fails to meet the other two criteria. Despite spatacsin being a large protein of approximately 2,443 amino acids involved in lysosomal function and autophagy, no experimentally-determined three-dimensional structure of SPG11/spatacsin exists in the Protein Data Bank (PDB), likely due to the protein's large size and structural complexity. Additionally, SPG11 is not catalogued as a drug target in the ChEMBL database, which is consistent with its role as a causative gene for a rare hereditary neurodegenerative disorder rather than a validated therapeutic target with associated small molecule modulators or clinical development compounds. Therefore, while SPG11 meets the first criterion regarding MANE Select annotation, it does not have either an experimental structure in PDB or a drug target entry in ChEMBL.

question: Summarize the taxonomic distribution, oxygen tolerance characteristics, and typical culture conditions for anaerobic bacteria documented in bacterial diversity databases.
ideal_answer: The BacDive database documents 8,994 unique anaerobic strains (with 316 strains annotated under more than one category, yielding 9,310 total category assignments): 4,776 annotated as "anaerobe," 4,310 as "facultative anaerobe," and 224 as "obligate anaerobe." Across all three categories, Firmicutes is the dominant phylum, contributing 2,096 anaerobes, 1,686 facultative anaerobes, and 94 obligate anaerobes; Proteobacteria ranks second among anaerobes (810) and ties with Firmicutes among facultative anaerobes (1,683); Actinobacteria accounts for 676 anaerobes and 490 facultative anaerobes, while Bacteroidetes contributes 351 anaerobes and 111 facultative anaerobes. At the order level, Lactobacillales leads with 1,557 strains, followed by Clostridiales (861), Enterobacterales (741), Actinomycetales (557), and Eubacteriales (409). Temperature data from BacDive's structured CultureTemperature records show that general anaerobes (4,707 strains with temperature data) grow across an extraordinarily broad range of −2 to 103°C with an average optimum near 36.4°C, facultative anaerobes (4,224 strains) span 0–90°C with a cooler mean of 26.8°C reflecting their greater ecological breadth, and obligate anaerobes (216 strains) average 36.9°C with a range of −1.8 to 112°C indicating adaptation to extreme environments. Cross-database integration with MediaDive identifies 4,984 anaerobic strains with linked medium records; the most commonly used media are Columbia Blood Medium (744 strains), EG Medium (402), Trypticase Soy Yeast Extract Medium (357), PYG Medium modified (330), and BL Agar (249), reflecting the nutritionally rich, reduced-oxygen formulations required by these organisms.
baseline_answer: Anaerobic bacteria are taxonomically diverse, distributed across numerous phyla including Firmicutes (containing genera such as Clostridium, Bacteroides, and Peptococcus), Bacteroidetes, Fusobacteria, Actinobacteria, and Proteobacteria, with significant representation also found in Spirochaetes and various candidate phyla. These organisms exhibit varying oxygen tolerance characteristics: obligate anaerobes are killed by atmospheric oxygen concentrations and include strict anaerobes like Clostridium perfringens and Bacteroides fragilis; aerotolerant anaerobes can survive oxygen exposure but do not use it for metabolism; and facultative anaerobes such as Escherichia coli can switch between aerobic and anaerobic metabolism. Typical culture conditions require oxygen-free environments achieved through anaerobic chambers, jars with gas-generating systems, or pre-reduced media containing reducing agents like cysteine, thioglycollate, or dithiothreitol. Media formulations commonly include supplementation with hemin, vitamin K, yeast extract, and volatile fatty acids, while maintaining pH between 6.8-7.5 and incubation temperatures ranging from 35-37°C for mesophiles to higher temperatures for thermophilic species. Selective media often incorporate antibiotics or bile salts to isolate specific groups, and redox indicators such as resazurin monitor oxygen levels in cultures. Fastidious anaerobes require additional growth factors including short-chain fatty acids, branched-chain amino acids, and specific vitamins, while some environmental anaerobes from extreme habitats may require specialized conditions such as high salt concentrations, extreme pH values, or elevated pressures.
togomcp_answer: Based on the comprehensive information gathered from multiple biological databases, anaerobic bacteria represent a diverse group of microorganisms distributed across multiple phyla within both the bacterial and archaeal domains. Taxonomically, obligate anaerobes are predominantly found within the phyla Firmicutes (including the orders Clostridiales with genera such as Clostridium, and families like Thermolithobacteraceae), Bacteroidetes (order Bacteroidales with the clinically significant Bacteroides fragilis group), Actinobacteria (anaerobic Actinomycetes including genera like Propionibacterium), and Proteobacteria (including Dehalococcoidales and anaerobic Campylobacter species), as well as archaeal lineages such as the order Methanobacteriales within Euryarchaeota. Facultative anaerobes like Klebsiella, Escherichia, and Streptococcus species can grow both aerobically and anaerobically. Oxygen tolerance characteristics define three major categories: obligate anaerobes that are killed by normal atmospheric oxygen concentrations and exhibit independence from oxygen for energy metabolism, microaerophiles like Propionibacterium acnes that tolerate low oxygen concentrations, and facultative anaerobes that can switch between aerobic respiration and fermentation depending on oxygen availability. Culture conditions for anaerobic bacteria require specialized techniques including anaerobic chambers or jars to maintain oxygen-free environments, use of pre-reduced anaerobic culture media often supplemented with reducing agents, incubation temperatures typically ranging from 30-37°C with some thermophiles requiring higher temperatures, and pH conditions that vary by species but commonly fall between pH 6.5-7.5, with acidophilic species like certain purple nonsulfur bacteria tolerating pH as low as 3.7. Growth substrates include complex organic compounds, with many species capable of mixed-acid fermentation under anaerobic conditions, and some utilizing specialized carbon sources such as dissolved inorganic carbon for photoautotrophs or glycerol in coral-associated species. Antimicrobial susceptibility patterns show that obligate anaerobes typically demonstrate 100% susceptibility to metronidazole, vancomycin, and ertapenem, though resistance to clindamycin occurs in 25-50% of certain Bacteroides and Clostridium species.

question: Which human enzymes with catalytic roles in the leukotriene and eoxin biosynthesis pathway are documented drug targets in ChEMBL with mechanism-of-action records?
ideal_answer: Five of the eight human enzymes with catalytic roles in the Reactome leukotriene and eoxin biosynthesis pathway have mechanism-of-action records in ChEMBL. Arachidonate 5-lipoxygenase (ALOX5, CHEMBL215) has the most ChEMBL mechanism records of any pathway enzyme, with eight drugs documented as inhibitors, including zileuton (phase 4), the only FDA-approved drug specifically indicated for asthma that acts by reversibly inhibiting this rate-limiting step in leukotriene synthesis, as well as five other phase-4 anti-inflammatory agents (mesalamine, sulfasalazine, balsalazide disodium, olsalazine sodium, meclofenamate sodium) and two phase-2 clinical candidates (PF-4191834, atreleuton). The 5-lipoxygenase-activating protein (ALOX5AP/FLAP, CHEMBL4550) is the most clinically active target, with three distinct phase-3 clinical inhibitors — fiboflapon, fiboflapon sodium, and veliflapon — all documented as INHIBITOR mechanisms. Leukotriene A4 hydrolase (LTA4H, CHEMBL4618), which converts LTA4 to the potent chemoattractant LTB4, is targeted by acebilustat at phase 2. The multidrug resistance-associated protein ABCC1/MRP1 (CHEMBL3004), which exports LTC4 across the cell membrane as part of the pathway, is targeted by the phase-2 multidrug resistance modulator biricodar. MAP kinase-activated protein kinase 2 (MAPKAPK2, CHEMBL2208), which activates ALOX5 via phosphorylation, is targeted at phase 1 by AT-13148, a broad-spectrum kinase inhibitor. Three pathway enzymes — arachidonate 15-lipoxygenase (ALOX15), prostaglandin reductase 1 (PTGR1), and leukotriene C4 synthase (LTC4S) — lack ChEMBL mechanism records despite participating in the pathway, reflecting their lower prioritisation as drug targets in clinical development programmes.
baseline_answer: The human enzymes with catalytic roles in leukotriene and eoxin biosynthesis that are documented drug targets in ChEMBL with mechanism-of-action records include ALOX5 (arachidonate 5-lipoxygenase), LTA4H (leukotriene A4 hydrolase), and LTC4S (leukotriene C4 synthase). ALOX5 catalyzes the first committed step in leukotriene biosynthesis by converting arachidonic acid to leukotriene A4 and is targeted by inhibitors such as zileuton, which is used clinically for asthma management. LTA4H converts leukotriene A4 to leukotriene B4 and has documented inhibitors in ChEMBL, though none are currently approved drugs. LTC4S conjugates leukotriene A4 with glutathione to form leukotriene C4, the precursor of cysteinyl leukotrienes, and while inhibitors have been developed and documented in ChEMBL, none have achieved clinical approval. ALOX15 (arachidonate 15-lipoxygenase), which catalyzes eoxin biosynthesis through the 15-lipoxygenation of arachidonic acid, also appears in ChEMBL as a documented target with associated mechanism-of-action records, though therapeutic agents targeting this enzyme remain investigational. These enzymes represent key control points in the inflammatory lipid mediator pathways, with ALOX5 being the only target with an approved drug demonstrating clinical efficacy.

question:
Which parent disease category of systemic lupus erythematosus has the most diseases with confirmed MeSH TopicalDescriptor mappings?

Choose one of the following options:
  - immune system disorder
  - autoimmune disease
  - connective tissue disorder
  - rheumatic disorder
ideal_answer: Immune system disorder (MONDO:0005046) has the most diseases with confirmed MeSH TopicalDescriptor mappings among the four parent categories of systemic lupus erythematosus, with 248 confirmed MeSH TopicalDescriptors across its disease subclasses. This substantially exceeds connective tissue disorder (134 TopicalDescriptors), autoimmune disease (61 TopicalDescriptors), and rheumatic disorder (39 TopicalDescriptors). The counts reflect confirmed joins with the MeSH RDF graph restricted to meshv:TopicalDescriptor entries (i.e., canonical MeSH headings used for indexing); MONDO cross-references to MeSH supplementary concept records (MESH:C...) are excluded. The four categories are not mutually exclusive: immune system disorder is the broadest and contains the other three as subcategories, so their diseases are counted within it as well — the sum across categories (482) exceeds the 346 unique diseases with TopicalDescriptor mappings due to this intentional overlap in the ontology hierarchy. The higher absolute count for immune system disorder reflects its greater scope rather than a higher per-disease mapping rate, since autoimmune disease and rheumatic disorder actually have proportionally good coverage relative to their size.
baseline_answer:
The correct answer is **autoimmune disease**.

Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is classified under multiple parent disease categories in medical ontologies, including autoimmune disease, immune system disorder, connective tissue disorder, and rheumatic disorder. Among these categories, autoimmune disease contains the most diseases with confirmed MeSH TopicalDescriptor mappings because it represents a broad, well-defined pathophysiological category that encompasses numerous specific disease entities systematically catalogued in MeSH (Medical Subject Headings). The autoimmune disease category includes hundreds of distinct conditions where the immune system attacks self-antigens, and MeSH has extensively mapped these diseases with topical descriptors for indexing purposes. While immune system disorder is a broader parent category that technically includes autoimmune diseases, and both connective tissue disorder and rheumatic disorder are relevant to SLE's clinical manifestations, the autoimmune disease category specifically has been more comprehensively mapped in MeSH due to its clear mechanistic definition and clinical importance, resulting in more confirmed TopicalDescriptor mappings for diseases within this category.

question: How many distinct PubChem compounds participate in chlorophyll and bacteriochlorophyll biosynthesis reactions documented in Rhea?
ideal_answer: Chlorophyll and bacteriochlorophyll biosynthesis involves the enzymatic conversion of tetrapyrrole precursors into photosynthetically active pigments. The Rhea database documents these biochemical reactions by linking them to chemical entities in ChEBI. Querying Rhea reactions whose equation text mentions "chlorophyll" or "bacteriochlorophyll" and extracting their associated ChEBI compound identifiers (via the rh:chebi property) yields 64 unique ChEBI chemical entities involved in these pathways. These ChEBI classes serve as type annotations for PubChem compound entries (via rdf:type assertions), enabling cross-database integration. Filtering for PubChem compounds (those with URIs starting with "http://rdf.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubchem/compound/") that are typed by any of these 64 ChEBI classes yields 24 distinct compounds. These include central pathway intermediates such as protoporphyrinogen IX, Mg-protoporphyrin IX, and various chlorophyllide derivatives, as well as cofactors like NADPH, ATP, and S-adenosyl-L-methionine. The substantially smaller number of PubChem entries relative to ChEBI classes reflects the fact that many highly specific tetrapyrrole intermediates and bacteriochlorophyll precursors, though well-defined in ChEBI, do not yet have curated entries in PubChem.
baseline_answer: I don't have access to real-time queries of the Rhea database or PubChem to provide an exact count of distinct compounds participating in chlorophyll and bacteriochlorophyll biosynthesis reactions. The Rhea database is a comprehensive resource for biochemical reactions that integrates with ChEBI (Chemical Entities of Biological Interest) and cross-references PubChem compound identifiers, but determining the precise number of distinct PubChem compounds involved in these specific biosynthetic pathways would require direct database querying capabilities that I cannot perform. The chlorophyll and bacteriochlorophyll biosynthesis pathways share common precursors and intermediates up to protoporphyrin IX, after which they diverge, involving numerous enzymatic steps with substrates, products, and cofactors that would each have PubChem identifiers. To obtain this specific numerical answer, one would need to query the Rhea database directly, filter for reactions annotated with chlorophyll and bacteriochlorophyll biosynthesis pathways, extract all associated PubChem compound identifiers, and count the unique entries.

question: Does human decorin (UniProt:P07585) have documented glycosylation sites in the GlyCosmos database?
ideal_answer: Yes, human decorin (UniProt:P07585) has documented glycosylation sites in the GlyCosmos database. Decorin is a small leucine-rich proteoglycan bearing glycosylation at six distinct amino acid positions: 34, 115, 211, 255, 262, and 303. The database records 286 total glycosylation site entries for decorin, reflecting the multiple glycan structures (glycoforms) annotated at individual positions — position 211 alone carries 132 distinct glycoform entries and position 262 carries 121, indicating extensive N-glycan microheterogeneity at these asparagine residues. The site at position 34 corresponds to the canonical glycosaminoglycan (chondroitin/dermatan sulfate) attachment serine characteristic of the proteoglycan core protein. This rich glycosylation complexity is consistent with decorin's biological roles in extracellular matrix organization, collagen fibrillogenesis, and TGF-β sequestration, where the glycan chains modulate protein–protein interactions and tissue hydration.
baseline_answer: I cannot access external databases including GlyCosmos to verify the current glycosylation site documentation for human decorin (UniProt:P07585). However, based on my training knowledge, human decorin is a small leucine-rich proteoglycan that contains well-characterized glycosylation sites. Decorin has one glycosaminoglycan (GAG) attachment site at serine-34 (Ser34) in its N-terminal domain where a chondroitin sulfate or dermatan sulfate chain is attached, which is essential for its proteoglycan function. Additionally, decorin contains potential N-linked glycosylation sites, though the functional GAG attachment at Ser34 represents the most biologically significant and extensively studied glycosylation modification. question: Which 5 genes have the most documented pathogenic or likely pathogenic ClinVar variants for Joubert syndrome, ranked by variant count?
ideal_answer: Integrating NANDO rare disease registry data, MedGen medical genetics concepts, and ClinVar variant data across all 51 Joubert syndrome MedGen concepts reveals 190 distinct genes with documented pathogenic or likely pathogenic variants. The five most heavily annotated are CEP290 (529 current P/LP variants), RPGRIP1L (255), CC2D2A (242), AHI1 (222), and TMEM67 (149). CEP290 encodes a centrosomal protein localised to primary cilia and is mutated across numerous ciliopathy subtypes including Joubert syndrome types 5 and 14, Bardet-Biedl syndrome, and nephronophthisis. RPGRIP1L (Joubert syndrome 7) and CC2D2A (Joubert syndrome 9) encode transition zone components critical for ciliary gate integrity, while AHI1 (jouberin, Joubert syndrome 3) mediates cerebellar and cortical development. TMEM67 (meckelin, Joubert syndrome 6) is a receptor-like transmembrane protein required for primary cilium formation. The high allelic burden in these genes reflects their role as major disease loci across multiple Joubert syndrome subtypes, the diagnostic importance of comprehensive multi-subtype variant cataloguing, and the evolutionary conservation of ciliary transition zone architecture.

question: Characterize the reviewed late proteins of Enterobacteria phage T4 across three dimensions: their GO-annotated functional module assignments (capsid, baseplate, and tail components); any enzymatic activities encoded among these otherwise structural late proteins; and their experimental structural coverage, including the relative proportions of cryo-electron microscopy versus X-ray crystallography depositions.
ideal_answer: The 25 reviewed late proteins of Enterobacteria phage T4, all annotated with KW-0426, collectively encode the phage's iconic contractile tail-injection nanomachine and partition into four major GO-defined structural modules: the capsid (2 proteins: CAPSH/major capsid protein, CAPSP/capsid vertex), the baseplate (11 proteins: the ten wedge and hub assembly proteins gp7, gp10, gp25, gp27, gp48, gp53, gp54, gp26, gp28, gp51, plus the pre-baseplate central spike gp5), the tail tube and completion system (4 proteins: gp19 tube, tail tube terminator, tape-measure protein, gp15 tail completion protein), and the tail fibers (5 proteins: short fiber gp12, three long-fiber subunits gp35/gp36/gp37, and the long-fiber proximal subunit), with the structural collar protein fibritin (WAC) and two DNA helicase isoforms (uvsW and uvsW1) completing the set. Enzymatically, two late proteins break the "purely structural" expectation: gp5 (NEEDL_BPT4) bears lysozyme activity (GO:0003796) that hydrolyzes peptidoglycan in the bacterial cell wall to puncture the host envelope during injection, while the uvsW DNA helicases (GO:0043138, 3'-5' DNA helicase activity) drive late-phase recombination and repair, a function unusual for proteins expressed after DNA replication has begun. Of the 25 proteins, 17 (68%) are structurally characterized in PDB via at least one entry, yielding 149 distinct structures (103 by cryo-electron microscopy, 44 by X-ray crystallography, 2 by solution NMR); because T4 assemblies are large multi-subunit complexes—the baseplate alone contains 11 late proteins—the same PDB entry frequently references multiple T4 proteins, producing 182 total protein-to-entry attributions for 149 distinct structures (33 attribution counts arise from co-occurrence in assemblies). The striking dominance of cryo-EM (69% of entries) reflects the field's shift toward studying intact viral assemblies: fibritin alone accounts for 104 of these entries due to its adoption as an engineering scaffold, while the gp5 spike (18 entries) and major capsid protein (9 entries) follow; the eight structurally uncharacterized proteins—most notably the three baseplate hub proteins gp26, gp28, and gp51, the two long tail-fiber subunits gp35 and gp36, and the two uvsW helicase isoforms—represent current frontiers in T4 structural biology.
baseline_answer: The late proteins of Enterobacteria phage T4 comprise approximately 40 structural components organized into three primary GO-annotated functional modules: the icosahedral capsid (including major capsid protein gp23, vertex proteins gp24 and gp20, portal protein gp20, and associated decoration proteins), the contractile tail sheath and tube (gp18 and gp19 respectively, plus tail terminator proteins), and the elaborate baseplate complex (containing at least 15 different proteins including gp5, gp6, gp7, gp8, gp9, gp10, gp11, gp12, gp25, gp27, gp48, gp53, and gp54 that assemble into a hexagonal hub with attached tail fibers). Despite their predominantly structural roles, several late proteins possess enzymatic activities essential for infection: gp5 contains a C-terminal lysozyme domain that degrades peptidoglycan during host cell wall penetration, while the long tail fibers (gp37) include endosialidase activity for receptor binding on host surfaces. The structural coverage of T4 late proteins has been extensively characterized through complementary techniques, with approximately 60-70% of late protein structures now resolved. X-ray crystallography has provided atomic-resolution structures for individual protein domains and smaller subassemblies, including the gp5-gp27 complex, baseplate hub components, and tail fiber proteins, while cryo-electron microscopy has become dominant for larger assemblies and near-complete virion structures, yielding high-resolution reconstructions of the entire baseplate, the tail-baseplate junction, and the complete capsid with decoration proteins at resolutions reaching 3-4 Ångströms. The cryo-EM depositions now substantially outnumber X-ray structures for multi-component assemblies, reflecting the method's superiority for large, complex macromolecular machines, though crystallographic structures remain valuable for detailed active site characterization in enzymatic late proteins.
togomcp_answer:
Based on the comprehensive literature search through PubMed, I now have sufficient information to answer the question about T4 phage late structural proteins. Let me compile the answer based on the retrieved data from the key references.

According to PubMed, the reviewed late proteins of Enterobacteria phage T4 exhibit distinct organizational patterns across three key dimensions. Structurally, the virion comprises approximately 300 gene products distributed among three primary GO-annotated functional modules: the icosahedral capsid (including the major capsid protein gp23 and portal protein gp20), the contractile tail apparatus (containing the tail tube protein gp19 and tail sheath protein gp18), and the multiprotein baseplate complex (assembled from components including gp5, gp6, gp7, gp8, gp10, gp27, and gp53 arranged in a dome-shaped, sixfold-symmetric structure approximately 520 Å in diameter) ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1128/MMBR.67.1.86-156.2003), [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1038/nsb970), [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1186/1743-422X-7-355)). Embedded within these ostensibly structural assemblies are several enzymatic activities that facilitate infection, most notably the triple lysozyme domain of gp5 that locally dissolves the periplasmic peptidoglycan layer during cell puncture, representing a rare example of enzymatic function encoded within a late structural gene product ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1038/415553a), [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/s1357-2725(02)00098-5)). Regarding experimental structural coverage, T4 late proteins demonstrate a hybrid characterization landscape wherein X-ray crystallography has resolved atomic-resolution structures of individual baseplate components including the gp5-gp27 complex at 2.9 Å resolution and the hubless baseplate wedge assembly at 4.0 Å resolution, while cryo-electron microscopy has provided near-atomic resolution structures of larger assemblies such as the portal protein gp20 at 3.6 Å, the intact extended tail at 15 Å, and the complete baseplate-tail tube complex at 12 Å resolution, indicating that approximately one-third of the ~20 tail structural proteins have been crystallographically determined and subsequently fitted into cryo-EM reconstructions to elucidate the full virion architecture ([DOI](https://doi.org/10.1038/nsmb975), [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1038/ncomms8548), [DOI](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jsb.2014.06.008)).

question:
Among the bacterial orders Hyphomicrobiales, Burkholderiales, Eubacteriales, and Pseudomonadales, which has the highest number of nitrogenase structural genes (nifH or nifD) represented in the NCBI Gene database?

Choose one of the following options:
  - Hyphomicrobiales
  - Burkholderiales
  - Eubacteriales
  - Pseudomonadales
ideal_answer: Hyphomicrobiales has the highest number of nitrogenase structural genes (nifH and nifD) among the four orders, with 66 annotated genes across 27 sequenced organisms in the NCBI Gene database. This order, which includes well-studied nitrogen-fixing alpha-proteobacteria such as Rhizobium phaseoli (6 genes), Rhodopseudomonas palustris (4 genes), and Xanthobacter autotrophicus (4 genes), is the predominant source of characterized nitrogenase genes in current genomic databases, reflecting decades of genome sequencing focused on agriculturally important symbiotic and free-living diazotrophs. Eubacteriales (formerly Clostridiales) ranks second with 19 nifH/nifD genes from 8 organisms, including Clostridium pasteurianum DSM 525 (7 genes) as the dominant contributor, alongside other anaerobic nitrogen fixers such as Clostridium tyrobutyricum (3 genes) and Clostridium beijerinckii (2 genes). Burkholderiales has 11 genes from 5 organisms including the endophyte Herbaspirillum seropedicae, while Pseudomonadales has only 7 genes from 2 organisms, notably Azotobacter chroococcum. The dominance of Hyphomicrobiales (66 genes, 64% of the 103 genes in these four orders) reflects the extensive genome sequencing of alpha-proteobacterial diazotrophs and the multiple nifH/nifD paralogs retained in some of these organisms. Across the full NCBI Gene database, 375 nifH/nifD genes span 174 organisms, demonstrating that nitrogen fixation capability is phylogenetically scattered well beyond these four orders, including in diverse Archaea (e.g., Methanocaldococcus) and sulfate-reducing bacteria.
baseline_answer:
**Burkholderiales** is the correct answer.

Burkholderiales contains the highest number of nitrogenase structural genes (nifH and nifD) in the NCBI Gene database among these four orders. This order includes numerous well-characterized nitrogen-fixing bacteria, particularly within families such as Burkholderiaceae and Rhodocyclaceae. Notable nitrogen-fixing genera include Burkholderia, Cupriavidus (formerly Ralstonia), and various diazotrophic members that are free-living soil bacteria, plant symbionts, or environmental nitrogen fixers. While Hyphomicrobiales also contains important nitrogen-fixing bacteria (including rhizobia like Rhizobium, Bradyrhizobium, and Sinorhizobium), Burkholderiales has been shown through genomic surveys to have a greater total representation of nif genes in sequence databases. Pseudomonadales includes very few nitrogen-fixing species (with Azotobacter and Azomonas being notable exceptions), and Eubacteriales (now largely reclassified within Clostridiales) has limited representation of nitrogen-fixing capacity compared to the alpha- and beta-proteobacterial orders. The abundance of sequenced Burkholderiales genomes combined with the widespread distribution of nitrogen fixation capability in this order accounts for its highest representation in gene databases.
togomcp_answer:
**Hyphomicrobiales**

Hyphomicrobiales has the highest number of nitrogenase structural genes (nifH or nifD) in the NCBI Gene database with 265 genes, substantially more than the other three orders. Burkholderiales contains 58 genes, Eubacteriales has 67 genes, and Pseudomonadales has only 22 genes. The dominance of Hyphomicrobiales reflects the prevalence of nitrogen-fixing capability within this order, which includes well-known diazotrophic groups such as Rhizobiales (containing the agriculturally important rhizobia) and Bradyrhizobiaceae, both of which form symbiotic associations with legumes and contribute significantly to biological nitrogen fixation in terrestrial ecosystems.

question: Does Anabaena sp. DSM 101043 grow in nitrogen-free BG11- medium?
ideal_answer: Yes, Anabaena sp. DSM 101043 (BacDive ID 131407) is documented to grow in Cyanobacteria Medium BG11-, which is a nitrogen-free medium used to induce heterocyst formation in nitrogen-fixing cyanobacteria. A MediaDive query confirmed zero nitrogen-containing ingredients (no nitrate, nitrite, ammonium, or urea) in BG11-, establishing that the strain grows without any external fixed-nitrogen source. BG11- medium lacks fixed nitrogen sources, requiring nitrogen-fixing strains like Anabaena to form specialized heterocyst cells for atmospheric nitrogen fixation. This psychrophilic strain isolated from sediment can fix atmospheric nitrogen through the nitrogenase enzyme complex housed within heterocysts, specialized anaerobic cells that protect oxygen-sensitive nitrogenase from photosynthetic oxygen production. The cross-database integration between BacDive (strain characterization) and MediaDive (validated cultivation protocols) confirms this nitrogen-independent growth capability.
baseline_answer: Anabaena sp. DSM 101043, like other members of the genus Anabaena, is a filamentous cyanobacterium capable of fixing atmospheric nitrogen through specialized cells called heterocysts. This organism can grow in nitrogen-free BG11- medium (BG11 medium without combined nitrogen sources such as nitrate or ammonium) by utilizing its nitrogen-fixing capability. When cultured in nitrogen-depleted conditions, Anabaena species develop heterocysts along their filaments, which provide a microanaerobic environment necessary for the oxygen-sensitive nitrogenase enzyme complex to convert atmospheric N₂ into ammonia for cellular use. The BG11- medium provides all other essential nutrients including phosphorus, trace metals, and carbon sources while deliberately omitting combined nitrogen, making it a standard medium for cultivating and studying diazotrophic cyanobacteria. Growth in this medium may be slower initially compared to nitrogen-replete conditions, as the organism must invest energy in heterocyst differentiation and nitrogen fixation, but sustained growth is achievable through this autotrophic nitrogen metabolism.
togomcp_answer: I cannot find specific information about Anabaena sp. DSM 101043 in the available databases or literature. However, Anabaena species are well-characterized nitrogen-fixing cyanobacteria that typically grow in nitrogen-free BG11 medium (designated BG11₀ or BG11-) due to their ability to fix atmospheric nitrogen through specialized cells called heterocysts. According to articles in PubMed, Anabaena species including *A. variabilis* ([DOI: 10.1007/s11120-015-0089-x](https://doi.org/10.1007/s11120-015-0089-x)) and *A. siamensis* ([DOI: 10.1016/j.biortech.2012.05.052](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biortech.2012.05.052)) are routinely cultivated in nitrogen-free BG11 medium, where they differentiate heterocysts and fix atmospheric nitrogen to support growth. Additionally, research by Tsavkelova et al. demonstrated that Anabaena can be isolated and grown on nitrogen-free variants of BG-11 medium. Since Anabaena sp. DSM 101043 belongs to this genus and shares the fundamental nitrogen-fixing capability characteristic of Anabaena, it would be expected to grow in nitrogen-free BG11- medium through diazotrophic growth, though growth rates may be 40-60% slower compared to cultures supplemented with combined nitrogen sources such as nitrate.

question: List all AMR element symbols associated with mupirocin resistance (MUPIROCIN class) in Staphylococcus aureus (NCBI taxon ID 1280) according to genomic resistance surveillance records, along with the count of isolate records for each element.
ideal_answer: Three AMR element symbols conferring mupirocin resistance are annotated in Staphylococcus aureus (NCBI taxon 1280) genotype records: mupA with 330 records, ileS_V588F with 90 records, and ileS_V631F with 5 records (total 425 genotype features; arithmetic check: 330+90+5=425). mupA encodes an acquired isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase paralog and is the primary determinant of high-level mupirocin resistance (MIC ≥512 mg/L), enabling competitive exclusion of mupirocin from the active site. ileS_V588F and ileS_V631F are point mutations in the native chromosomal ileS gene encoding the endogenous isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase and confer low-level resistance (MIC 8–256 mg/L). The predominance of mupA in surveillance records reflects its plasmid-mediated transmissibility, which facilitates its spread among clinical MRSA lineages, whereas ileS mutations arise independently and are less common. The distinction between high-level (mupA) and low-level (ileS mutations) resistance has direct clinical implications, as high-level resistance compromises mupirocin use for MRSA decolonization regimens.

The mupB gene confers low-level resistance (MIC 8-256 μg/mL) and is detected less frequently, generally in hundreds to low thousands of isolate records. Chromosomal ileS mutations causing amino acid substitutions at specific positions (commonly V588F, F631I, and others) result in low-level resistance and are documented in hundreds of isolates. The mupR regulatory gene, which is often co-located with mupA on plasmids, may also be catalogued in surveillance systems. question:
Among Mucopolysaccharidosis types I, II, III, IV, and VI, which type has the highest number of PubMed articles with co-annotated gene mentions documented in PubTator Central?

Choose one of the following options:
  - Mucopolysaccharidosis type I (Hurler syndrome)
  - Mucopolysaccharidosis type II (Hunter syndrome)
  - Mucopolysaccharidosis type III (Sanfilippo syndrome)
  - Mucopolysaccharidosis type IV (Morquio syndrome)
  - Mucopolysaccharidosis type VI (Maroteaux-Lamy syndrome)
ideal_answer: Mucopolysaccharidosis type III (Sanfilippo syndrome, MeSH:D009084) has the highest number of PubMed articles with co-annotated gene mentions in PubTator Central, with 7,826 articles (requiring gene annotations to be verified as NCBI-registered genes). This is substantially more than MPS type I (Hurler syndrome, MeSH:D008059) with 3,505 articles, MPS type II (Hunter syndrome, MeSH:D016532) with 2,413 articles, MPS type IV (Morquio syndrome, MeSH:D009085) with 2,338 articles, and MPS type VI (Maroteaux-Lamy syndrome, MeSH:D009087) with 1,030 articles. The sum of per-type counts (17,112) exceeds the count of unique articles across all five types (13,644), indicating that approximately 3,468 articles discuss multiple MPS types simultaneously. The disproportionate annotation volume for MPS III likely reflects its four biochemically distinct subtypes (A–D, caused by SGSH, NAGLU, HGSNAT, and GNS respectively) and its complex neurological pathology—MPS III is the most prevalent lysosomal storage disorder affecting the central nervous system and has attracted substantial genetics, biomarker, and gene therapy research. In contrast, MPS VI has a narrower somatic phenotype without CNS involvement, correlating with fewer publications.

question: Does the bacterial genome assembly CP036276.1 of Symmachiella dynata strain Mal52 encode more than one copy of the 16S ribosomal RNA gene?
ideal_answer: The bacterial genome assembly CP036276.1 of Symmachiella dynata strain Mal52 encodes two copies of the 16S ribosomal RNA gene. The first copy is located at positions 436,264–437,809 bp on the forward strand, and the second copy at positions 5,256,596–5,258,141 bp on the reverse strand. Together with a 23S ribosomal RNA gene (1,040,576–1,043,484 bp) and a 5S ribosomal RNA gene (1,043,659–1,043,768 bp), the genome harbors four ribosomal RNA features in total. The spatial arrangement of the 23S and 5S rRNA genes adjacent to the first 16S copy suggests that these three form a classical prokaryotic rRNA operon (16S-23S-5S), while the second 16S copy at a distant locus may represent an incomplete or independent operon. The presence of multiple 16S rRNA gene copies is commonly associated with the capacity for faster ribosome production and more rapid adaptation to nutrient availability, as rRNA gene copy number correlates with maximum growth rate in bacteria. This structural information is retrievable directly from the INSDC nucleotide sequence record via the DDBJ RDF endpoint, with features linked to NCBI Taxonomy identifier 2527995 through the RO:in taxon relationship.

question: Summarize the human proteasome protein landscape as defined by the UniProt keyword KW-0647 (Proteasome), characterizing the distribution across GO cellular component subcomplexes (20S core, 19S regulatory, accessory), the overlap in multi-subcomplex annotations, and the fraction represented as ChEMBL drug targets.
ideal_answer: There are 53 reviewed human proteins classified under UniProt keyword KW-0647 (Proteasome), forming a structurally and functionally diverse complex system. When distributed across eight GO cellular component subcategories using structured ontology IRIs, 49 of these proteins are annotated to the general proteasome complex (GO:0000502), while the 20S core complex (GO:0005839) accounts for 18 proteins, the accessory complex (GO:0022624) for 16, the core beta-subunit complex (GO:0019774) for 11, the regulatory particle base subcomplex (GO:0008540) for 9, the lid subcomplex (GO:0008541) for 8, the alpha-subunit complex (GO:0019773) for 8, and the 19S regulatory particle (GO:0005838) for 7. The sum of these category counts reaches 126 annotations for 52 uniquely annotated proteins (arithmetic verification: 126 > 52 = valid overlap), reflecting extensive multi-subcomplex co-annotation — for example, a beta subunit is simultaneously annotated to the general proteasome complex, the 20S core, and the beta-subunit complex. Four proteins lack the general GO:0000502 annotation entirely: PSMF1 (PI31 inhibitor), PSME4 (PA200 activator), PSB11 (inducible beta-11), and PSMA8 (testis-specific alpha-8). Three of them (PSMF1, PSB11, PSMA8) still appear in subcomplex categories (GO:0005839, GO:0019774, GO:0019773 respectively), while PSME4 carries none of the eight GO subcomplex annotations, consistent with its role as an externally docking activator rather than a structural subunit. Cross-referencing with ChEMBL reveals that 22 of the 53 proteins (41.5%) are registered as human single-protein drug targets, with all eight canonical beta subunits included — consistent with the clinical use of proteasome inhibitors such as bortezomib and carfilzomib that target the beta5 catalytic subunit (PSMB5).
baseline_answer: The human proteasome protein landscape encompasses approximately 45-50 proteins annotated with the UniProt keyword KW-0647 (Proteasome), distributed across three major functional categories based on GO cellular component annotations. The 20S core particle contains 14 constitutive subunits (7 alpha-type and 7 beta-type subunits forming four stacked heptameric rings) plus 3 immunoproteasome-specific catalytic subunits (β1i/PSMB9, β2i/PSMB10, β5i/PSMB8) that can replace their constitutive counterparts, totaling approximately 17 distinct proteins. The 19S regulatory particle comprises roughly 19 subunits divided into base (6 ATPase and 4 non-ATPase subunits) and lid (9 non-ATPase subunits) subcomplexes. Accessory proteins include PA28αβ (PSME1/PSME2) and PA28γ (PSME3) activator complexes, PA200 (PSME4), and additional assembly chaperones and regulatory factors, accounting for approximately 10-15 proteins. Multi-subcomplex annotation overlap is minimal since most proteins belong exclusively to either the 20S core or 19S regulatory particle, though some proteasome activators can interact with multiple forms and assembly chaperones transiently associate with core particle precursors. Regarding therapeutic relevance, the catalytic beta subunits (particularly β5/PSMB5, β1/PSMB6, β2/PSMB7, and immunoproteasome subunits) represent the primary ChEMBL drug targets, with FDA-approved proteasome inhibitors like bortezomib, carfilzomib, and ixazomib targeting these active sites, constituting approximately 15-20% of the total proteasome protein complement as established pharmacological targets.

question: Summarize the approved Rhea biochemical reactions catalyzed by the four gluconeogenesis-specific enzymes—pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1), GTP-dependent phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (EC 4.1.1.32), fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.11), and glucose-6-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.9)—covering the total number of approved Rhea reactions, the types of nucleotide cofactors involved (via ChEBI), and the number of reviewed human UniProt proteins annotated with each enzyme.
ideal_answer: Across the four gluconeogenesis-specific enzyme classes, Rhea contains 6 approved biochemical reactions in total: 1 for pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1, RHEA:20844), 2 for GTP-dependent phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (EC 4.1.1.32, RHEA:10388 and RHEA:64864), 1 for fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.11, RHEA:11064), and 2 for glucose-6-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.9, RHEA:16689 and RHEA:44904). Regarding nucleotide cofactors, pyruvate carboxylase uses ATP (CHEBI:15422) to drive the carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate, while the human GTP-dependent PEPCK isoform uses GTP (CHEBI:37565) to decarboxylate and phosphorylate oxaloacetate to phosphoenolpyruvate; the phosphohydrolases—fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase and glucose-6-phosphatase—require no nucleotide cofactor, instead cleaving phosphate ester bonds using water. In reviewed human UniProt entries, there is 1 protein for pyruvate carboxylase (PYC_HUMAN, P11498), 2 for GTP-dependent PEPCK (cytosolic PCKGC_HUMAN P35558 and mitochondrial PCKGM_HUMAN Q16822), 2 for fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (liver F16P1_HUMAN P09467 and muscle F16P2_HUMAN O00757), and 3 for glucose-6-phosphatase (G6PC1_HUMAN P35575, G6PC2_HUMAN Q9NQR9, and G6PC3_HUMAN Q9BUM1), giving 8 reviewed human proteins in total. This pattern reflects tissue-specific isoform diversification in the regulatory phosphatase steps, in contrast to the single isoform covering the biotin-dependent carboxylation step at the pathway entry point.
baseline_answer: The four gluconeogenesis-specific enzymes catalyze distinct sets of approved Rhea biochemical reactions with varying cofactor requirements and human protein representations. Pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1) catalyzes the ATP-dependent carboxylation of pyruvate to oxaloacetate, requiring ATP as a nucleotide cofactor and biotin as a prosthetic group, with one reviewed human UniProt protein (PC, P11498). GTP-dependent phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (EC 4.1.1.32) catalyzes the GTP-dependent decarboxylation and phosphorylation of oxaloacetate to phosphoenolpyruvate, utilizing GTP and GDP as nucleotide cofactors, with two reviewed human UniProt proteins representing the cytosolic (PCK1, P35558) and mitochondrial (PCK2, Q16822) isoforms. Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.11) catalyzes the hydrolysis of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to fructose-6-phosphate and inorganic phosphate without requiring nucleotide cofactors, with two reviewed human UniProt proteins corresponding to the liver (FBP1, P09467) and muscle (FBP2, O00757) isoforms. Glucose-6-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.9) catalyzes the final step, hydrolyzing glucose-6-phosphate to glucose and inorganic phosphate without nucleotide cofactor involvement, with three reviewed human UniProt proteins including the catalytic subunit (G6PC, P35575) and two glucose-6-phosphate transporter subunits (SLC37A4, O43826, and G6PC3, Q9BUM1). Collectively, these enzymes involve ATP, GTP, and GDP as the primary nucleotide cofactors across the gluconeogenesis pathway, with eight reviewed human proteins total representing the complete enzymatic machinery for this metabolic process.

Pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1) catalyzes one reaction (RHEA:20844) that converts pyruvate and bicarbonate to oxaloacetate using ATP as a cofactor, producing ADP (ChEBI:15422 for ATP, ChEBI:456216 for ADP). GTP-dependent phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (EC 4.1.1.32) catalyzes two reactions: RHEA:10388 using GTP (ChEBI:15996) to produce GDP and phosphoenolpyruvate from oxaloacetate, and RHEA:64864 using the alternative nucleotide cofactor ITP (ChEBI:16039) to produce IDP. Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.11) catalyzes one reaction (RHEA:11064) that hydrolyzes fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to fructose-6-phosphate without requiring nucleotide cofactors. Glucose-6-phosphatase (EC 3.1.3.9) catalyzes two reactions: RHEA:16689 converting D-glucose-6-phosphate to D-glucose and RHEA:44904 converting the alpha-anomer, both hydrolytic reactions without nucleotide cofactor involvement. Among the nucleotide cofactors identified, ATP and its product ADP participate in the pyruvate carboxylase reaction, while GTP/GDP and ITP/IDP serve as alternative cofactors for phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase. Human reviewed UniProt entries annotated with these enzymes include one protein for pyruvate carboxylase (P11498), two proteins for GTP-dependent phosphoenolpyruvate carboxykinase (P35558 and Q16822), two proteins for fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (P09467 and O00757), and three proteins for glucose-6-phosphatase (P35575, Q9NQR9, and Q9BUM1), totaling eight human enzymes across the four gluconeogenic activities.

question:
Among the voltage-gated potassium channel genes KCNQ2, KCNQ3, KCNB1, and KCNT1 — each causally linked to distinct epilepsy syndromes classified under the epilepsy disease class (MONDO:0005027) — which gene has the greatest number of pathogenic or likely pathogenic germline variants currently documented in ClinVar?

Choose one of the following options:
  - KCNQ2
  - KCNQ3
  - KCNB1
  - KCNT1
ideal_answer: Among the four voltage-gated potassium channel genes KCNQ2, KCNQ3, KCNB1, and KCNT1 — all associated with MONDO-classified epilepsy syndromes — KCNQ2 (gene ID 3785, chromosome 20q13.33) has by far the greatest number of pathogenic or likely pathogenic germline variants in ClinVar, with 759 such variants, compared to 118 for KCNT1, and 102 each for KCNB1 and KCNQ3 (ClinVar January 2025 release; arithmetic verification: sum 1,081 > total distinct 1,077, indicating 4 variants attributed to multiple genes). This substantial variant burden reflects KCNQ2's role as the causal gene for both the severe DEE7 (developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 7, MONDO:0013387) and the milder benign familial neonatal convulsions type 1, making it a major target of clinical sequencing in pediatric epilepsy. KCNQ2 and KCNQ3 encode the Kv7.2 and Kv7.3 subunits that co-assemble to form the neuronal M-channel responsible for regulating neuronal excitability; KCNQ2 variants are more frequently pathogenic and more clinically diverse in severity than KCNQ3 variants, which mainly cause the milder BFNC2 (MONDO:0007366). KCNT1 encodes the sodium-activated KNa1.1 (SLACK) channel and causes the severe epilepsy of infancy with migrating focal seizures (EIMFS, MONDO:0100025), while KCNB1 encodes the Kv2.1 delayed-rectifier channel associated with DEE34 (MONDO:0014718); both have a smaller but clinically significant variant spectrum compared to KCNQ2.
baseline_answer:
**KCNQ2** is correct.

KCNQ2 has the greatest number of pathogenic or likely pathogenic germline variants documented in ClinVar among these four voltage-gated potassium channel genes. This gene, which encodes the Kv7.2 potassium channel subunit, is the most frequently mutated of these genes in epilepsy, particularly associated with benign familial neonatal seizures (BFNS) and neonatal-onset epileptic encephalopathy. The higher number of documented variants in KCNQ2 reflects both its critical role in neuronal excitability and the extensive clinical and genetic screening that has occurred since its initial identification as an epilepsy gene in the late 1990s. While KCNQ3, KCNB1, and KCNT1 are all established epilepsy genes with documented pathogenic variants, they have each been associated with fewer reported cases and consequently fewer catalogued pathogenic variants in ClinVar. KCNQ2-related disorders represent one of the more common monogenic causes of neonatal seizures, which has led to more comprehensive variant reporting and curation in clinical databases.
togomcp_answer:
**KCNQ2**

KCNQ2 has the greatest number of pathogenic or likely pathogenic germline variants in ClinVar with 1,172 documented variants, substantially more than the other three voltage-gated potassium channel genes. KCNT1 ranks second with 342 variants, KCNQ3 has 309 variants, and KCNB1 has 243 variants. KCNQ2-related epilepsies, including benign familial neonatal seizures and neonatal-onset epileptic encephalopathy, represent a well-characterized spectrum with extensive clinical and molecular characterization, which likely contributes to the larger number of reported pathogenic variants in ClinVar compared to the other genes in this group.

question: Is 6,7-dimethyl-8-(1-D-ribityl)lumazine classified in PubChem as a pteridine (CHEBI:17601) and documented as a substrate in an approved Rhea reaction catalyzed by riboflavin synthase (EC 2.5.1.9)?
ideal_answer: Yes. 6,7-dimethyl-8-(1-D-ribityl)lumazine is classified in PubChem as the pteridine CHEBI:17601 (CID:168989), and its pH-7.3 microspecies (CHEBI:58201, CID:46931117) is documented as the direct substrate of the approved Rhea reaction RHEA:20772 catalyzed by riboflavin synthase (EC 2.5.1.9). In this reaction, two molecules of the lumazine intermediate undergo a dismutation: one is oxidized to release the four-carbon fragment that becomes the dimethylbenzene ring of riboflavin, while the other is reduced back to 5-amino-6-(D-ribitylamino)uracil, an earlier precursor in the riboflavin pathway. The reaction is chemically balanced, Approved in Rhea, and annotated with GO:0004746 (riboflavin synthase activity). The pteridine scaffold of the lumazine substrate is thus the direct biosynthetic precursor to the isoalloxazine ring system of riboflavin (vitamin B2).
baseline_answer: 6,7-dimethyl-8-(1-D-ribityl)lumazine is classified in PubChem as a pteridine derivative, as it contains the characteristic bicyclic pteridine ring system that defines CHEBI:17601. This compound serves as a substrate in the Rhea-catalyzed reaction performed by riboflavin synthase (EC 2.5.1.9), which converts two molecules of 6,7-dimethyl-8-(1-D-ribityl)lumazine into one molecule of riboflavin (vitamin B2) and one molecule of 5-amino-6-(1-D-ribitylamino)uracil through a dismutation mechanism. The reaction is documented in the Rhea database as an approved biochemical transformation, representing a key step in riboflavin biosynthesis found in bacteria, fungi, and plants. Riboflavin synthase catalyzes this unique reaction where the lumazine substrate acts as both a donor and acceptor of a four-carbon unit, making it essential for the de novo synthesis of this important vitamin cofactor precursor.

2. **Rhea reaction with EC 2.5.1.9**: From the Rhea data:

question: How many distinct approved biochemical reactions in the Rhea database are collectively annotated for the reviewed human enzymatic catalysts of the nicotinate metabolism pathway?
ideal_answer: The 22 reviewed human enzymatic catalysts of the Reactome nicotinate metabolism pathway are collectively annotated with 58 distinct approved reactions in the Rhea database. This repertoire encompasses the full biochemical breadth of these enzymes beyond their nicotinate-specific roles: the pathway itself covers the Preiss-Handler route (nicotinate → NaMN → deamido-NAD+ → NAD+ via NAPRT, NMNAT1-3, and NADSYN1), the NAD+ salvage route (nicotinamide → NMN → NAD+ via NAMPT and NMNATs), and NAD+ consumption and recycling steps (CD38/BST1 glycohydrolases, NNMT methyltransferase, NT5E nucleotidase). The per-enzyme Rhea contribution varies widely: the sodium-coupled monocarboxylate transporter SLC5A8 (Q8N695) links to 14 approved reactions reflecting its broad substrate range for short-chain carboxylates including nicotinate, while NT5E/CD73 (P21589) contributes 10 reactions covering all its nucleoside monophosphate substrates. CD38 (P28907) accounts for 6 reactions including NAD+ glycohydrolase, ADP-ribosyl cyclase, and cyclic ADP-ribose hydrolase activities. The 58-reaction total from 22 enzymes (68 protein-reaction pairs) reflects 10 shared reactions catalysed by multiple enzyme paralogues — for instance, the core NAD+ glycohydrolase reaction (Rhea:16301) is shared by both CD38 and BST1/CD157. In contrast, NAMPT, NADK, NAPRT, QPRT, and NNMT each contribute a single Rhea reaction reflecting their narrow substrate specificity, while NMNAT1 (Q9HAN9) contributes 2 approved reactions — covering both NMN (Rhea:21360) and NaMN (Rhea:22860) as substrates — consistent with its dual role in both the salvage and Preiss-Handler de novo routes to NAD+.

question: Which reviewed UniProt Bacillus subtilis (strain 168) proteins annotated with the biotin biosynthesis keyword have at least one deposited structure in the Protein Data Bank?
ideal_answer: Three of the seven reviewed Bacillus subtilis (strain 168, taxon:224308) proteins annotated with the biotin biosynthesis keyword (KW-0093) have at least one structure deposited in the Protein Data Bank, while four — BioB, BioD, BioF2, and BioF1 (kbl) — are structurally uncharacterized. The three with PDB entries correspond to enzymes of the B. subtilis-specific pimelate thioester synthesis route that differs fundamentally from the E. coli BioC/BioH pathway: BioW (BIOW_BACSU, P53559), the 6-carboxyhexanoate–CoA ligase that activates pimelate as its CoA thioester, has four deposited structures (including PDB:5G1F and substrate-bound complexes); BioK (BIOK_BACSU, P53555), the L-Lysine–8-amino-7-oxononanoate transaminase, has four structures (including PDB:3DOD); and BioI (BIOI_BACSU, P53554), the cytochrome P450 that oxidatively cleaves long-chain acyl-ACPs to generate the pimeloyl-ACP precursor, has three structures (including PDB:3EJB). Notably, BioB (BIOB_BACSU, P53557) — the radical SAM enzyme that inserts the sulfur atoms to form the biotin dithiolane ring, constituting the committed final step of biotin biosynthesis — lacks any deposited structure in UniProt's PDB cross-references, illustrating that structural characterization does not correlate simply with biochemical importance.

question: Summarize the genomic and clinical variant landscape of the eight human Bardet-Biedl syndrome genes (BBS1, BBS2, BBS4, BBS5, BBS7, BBS9, BBS10, and BBS12) by their chromosomal distribution, total variant burden per gene in ClinVar, and the breakdown of clinical significance categories across all eight genes.
ideal_answer: The eight canonical human Bardet-Biedl syndrome genes—BBS1, BBS2, BBS4, BBS5, BBS7, BBS9, BBS10, and BBS12—are distributed across seven distinct autosomes: chromosome 2 (BBS5), chromosome 4 (BBS7 and BBS12), chromosome 7 (BBS9), chromosome 11 (BBS1), chromosome 12 (BBS10), chromosome 15 (BBS4), and chromosome 16 (BBS2), making chromosome 4 the only chromosome harboring two of these genes. In the MeSH hierarchy, Bardet-Biedl syndrome (D020788) is classified simultaneously under congenital and hereditary ciliopathies (tree C16.131.077.245.125 and C16.320.184.125), retinitis pigmentosa within eye diseases (C11.270.684.624), and hypothalamic diseases (C10.228.140.617.200), reflecting the multi-system pathology of this ciliopathy. Together the eight genes harbor 7,800 distinct current ClinVar variants; BBS9 (1,283 variants) and BBS2 (1,258) carry the heaviest burdens, followed by BBS1 (1,193), BBS10 (1,007), BBS4 (900), BBS12 (868), BBS7 (849), and BBS5 (465, the lightest burden). By variant type, single nucleotide variants overwhelmingly dominate at 6,468 (83%), followed by deletions (666; 8.5%) and duplications (274; 3.5%). For clinical significance across all eight genes, the largest category is likely benign (2,808 variants), followed by variants of uncertain significance at 2,759, while pathogenic, likely pathogenic, and combined pathogenic/likely pathogenic entries total 1,638; 23 variants are counted in two BBS genes simultaneously, reflecting structural variants on chromosome 4 that overlap both BBS7 and BBS12.

Based on ClinVar data, BBS1 carries the highest variant burden with over 500 reported variants, followed by BBS10 with approximately 300-400 variants, while BBS2, BBS4, BBS7, and BBS9 each contain 100-250 variants, and BBS5 and BBS12 have relatively fewer entries with under 100 variants each. Across all eight genes collectively, the clinical significance breakdown shows that pathogenic and likely pathogenic variants together constitute approximately 40-50% of all reported variants, reflecting the well-characterized disease-causing mutations in these genes. Variants of uncertain significance (VUS) represent the largest single category at approximately 35-45% of total variants, highlighting ongoing challenges in variant interpretation for these genes. Benign and likely benign variants account for roughly 10-20% of entries, while conflicting interpretations of pathogenicity appear in 3-8% of cases. The remaining variants fall into other categories including risk factors or variants with no assertion of clinical significance. This distribution pattern reflects both the genetic heterogeneity of Bardet-Biedl syndrome and the varying levels of functional characterization across the BBS gene family.

BBS1 resides on chromosome 11 (11q13.2), BBS2 on chromosome 16 (16q13), BBS4 on chromosome 15 (15q24.1), BBS5 on chromosome 2 (2q31.1), BBS7 on chromosome 4 (4q27), BBS9 on chromosome 7 (7p14.3), BBS10 on chromosome 12 (12q21.2), and BBS12 on chromosome 4 (4q27), with BBS7 and BBS12 notably both mapping to the same chromosomal arm. The total ClinVar variant burden varies considerably across these genes: BBS1 harbors 1,264 variants, BBS2 contains 1,378 variants (the highest burden), BBS4 has 969 variants, BBS5 has 492 variants (the lowest), BBS7 contains 888 variants, BBS9 has 1,338 variants, BBS10 harbors 1,078 variants, and BBS12 contains 918 variants, yielding a cumulative total of 8,325 variants across all eight genes. The clinical significance breakdown reveals that pathogenic or likely pathogenic variants constitute approximately 323 variants for BBS1, 323 for BBS2, with similar proportions observed across the remaining genes, while benign or likely benign variants represent the majority classification with BBS1 having 701 benign variants, BBS2 having 745, and uncertain significance variants accounting for substantial portions with BBS1 containing 539 uncertain variants and BBS2 containing 665, demonstrating that the variant landscape for these BBS genes reflects a complex mix of definitively pathogenic mutations underlying Bardet-Biedl syndrome alongside a large proportion of benign polymorphisms and variants of uncertain clinical significance that require further functional characterization.
